<h2>2. Blossom</h2>

<p>While the first blossom appears in February, more appear in March and April, often with vivid raspberry pink petals. I feel the bunches of blossoms look like scoops of fluffy, fruity, ice cream, although that’s probably just me. The blooms are very short lived, about a week. So I recommend going out regularly, maybe taking different routes home, to catch them.</p>

<p>If you have even more time, I like to watch them as they buds burst, they bloom, and then the fall of their petals while the leaves come through. The colour of the tree changes so much over a couple of weeks, from brown to white or pink, and then often to a burgundy, as the green leaves merge with the remnants of the flowers, before ending with a fresh display of green leaves.</p>

