<h2>3. Bluebells</h2>

<p>I used to think bluebells were magic. From their purpley flowers looking like hats for tiny garden fairies (growing up, I was a big fan of the flower fairies by Cicely Mary Barker thanks to my mum and grandmother). To the fact that wild bluebells are found in woodlands, which I would rarely come across, and seen just a splash of violet in the corner of your eye. I considered them to be extremely rare and precious (almost as rare as the fairies I’d imagine to be close by).</p>

<p>However this year, since I’ve been taking special notice to look for wildlife, I’ve noticed bluebells everywhere. I’ve seen them grow between fences, between the boundaries of people’s gardens and the edge of pavements, and in little corners of grass and brick. However, they are still rare. Of the world’s bluebells, half of them are in the UK, and they can be very fragile and difficult to grow. So take care not to disturb them (or the fairies nearby).</p>

