<h2>4. Dandelions</h2>

<p>I’ve always found dandelions to be a staple of UK green spaces. Whether it be their vibrant frilly golden heads, which I’d play with as a child, while sitting with my friends on a sunny day. Or the seed clocks, that we’d blow to make a wish. They remind me of calm, peaceful times, without any hustle or bustle.</p>

<p>Since doing this wildlife watchlist I have noticed so many things, that I was oblivious to before. Firstly, the sheer scale of dandelions. I used to think of them as being quite spread out and sporadic, but this month (and April) I’ve found large swathes of them covering the ground very much like daffodils.</p>

<p>I’ve also read that they follow the sun like sunflowers. They open up after sunrise and turn their heads to the sun, then close up in the evening leaving a little tuft of yellow hair. Interestingly, their seed heads can tell you the weather. They need dry air to spread, and so will close up if there’s moisture in the air and coming rain.</p>

<p>Plus their lively yellow heads provide great food for butterflies, so avoid the temptation to pick them, and look for butterflies instead.</p>

